article.description: Ron Artest capped a contentious day by coming off the bench to score 18 points Monday in the Indiana Pacers' 94-86 win over the Memphis Grizzlies.
article.headline: Entering the game late, Artest energizes Pacers
article.linkText: Artest scores 18 to boost Pacers over Grizzlies
article.story: INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Maybe all Ron Artest needed was a little extra sleep. Artest was taken out of the starting lineup after he overslept and missed the morning shootaround, then capped a contentious few days by scoring 18 points Monday night in the Indiana Pacers' 94-86 win over the Memphis Grizzlies. "I thought Artest was a key guy in the game," Pacers coach Rick Carlisle said. "To come in and play the way he did under the circumstances of the last few days, we certainly needed it." Carlisle blasted Artest and the team after Saturday night's loss to the New Jersey Nets. Artest was benched for the entire second half of that game for poor shot selection and arguing with the coach at halftime. He met with Carlisle, CEO Donnie Walsh and president Larry Bird Monday afternoon to address the situation, then said he would not play because of a sore lower back. But he changed his mind shortly before gametime and entered with just under five minutes left in the first quarter, energizing a flat Pacers team. "We have a good training staff," Carlisle said with a wry smile. "I never believed he wasn't going to play." Artest shot 7-of-10 from the field with five rebounds and four assists and Jermaine O'Neal had 20 points and 13 rebounds as Indiana handed the Grizzlies their sixth straight loss. Carlisle said Artest was benched against the Nets for "conduct detrimental to winning," including the argument and taking three 3-pointers out of the flow of the offense. It appears the stern message got through to Artest. He attempted just one 3-pointer Monday at the end of the game. "We had a nice, long talk," Artest said of the meeting. "You get sidetracked sometimes, you just don't want to get sidetracked all the time." He threw down a fast-break dunk in the midst of a 10-0 run in the third quarter that helped the Pacers take control. O'Neal then scored six points to fuel a 10-2 run in the fourth quarter that sealed the game and snapped a two-game losing skid -- the first time the Pacers lost consecutive games all season. "It's huge to win and break a losing streak," Carlisle said. "You don't want to get to that third game, then things can spiral a little bit." Carlisle was also pleased with the defensive intensity in the second half, something that has been sorely lacking during the team's 7-8 skid over the previous 15 games. The Pacers held Memphis to 33 points on 31 percent shooting in the second half. "They're one of the better defensive teams in the league," Memphis forward Bonzi Wells said. "That's what good teams do right there -- shut you down." Pau Gasol led the Grizzlies with 20 points and eight rebounds. Wells added 16 points, but sat out most of the fourth quarter after colliding with Jeff Foster. Foster went up for a dunk and hit Wells in the face as he stepped in to take a charge. Wells left with a bloody nose and sat on the bench holding an ice pack on his face for the rest of the game. Grizzlies coach Hubie Brown said Wells' absence was no excuse. "They out-toughed us," Brown said. "They deserve the win." The win, for the moment, helped the Pacers put the distractions created by Artest behind them. "He's a brother to us and we're behind him," O'Neal said. "We've just got to keep talking to each other." Carlisle said Artest apologized on Monday and an understanding was reached. "It's over with. It's in the past and been talked about and we're moving on," Carlisle said. Game Notes: The Pacers had another rough night with the officials. In Saturday's loss, Carlisle was ejected and Reggie Miller and O'Neal each received technical fouls for arguing with the referees. On Monday, Miller and O'Neal both got technical fouls in the first half. ... Memphis G Jason Williams received a technical with 2:19 to play for arguing. ... Mike Miller nailed a 3 from the top of the key as time expired in the first quarter. But after reviewing the play, officials ruled that he didn't get the ball out of his hand before the buzzer. ... Memphis (0-8) is the only NBA team to have never beaten the Pacers in Indiana. The Pacers are 14-2 against the Grizzlies, and their two losses have been in their only two appearances in Memphis.
